// Criminal Procedure Code [Act 593] — the SEARCH / ARREST cluster, chosen for
// the flagship "can a police officer go through my phone?" scenario (roadblock
// or walk-and-stop). The spine: s20 (search of person on arrest — where the
// phone physically changes hands), s20A (Fourth Schedule body-search procedure
// binds EVERY enforcement agency), s116B (ACCESS TO COMPUTERIZED DATA — the
// express phone/data provision: an Inspector-and-above conducting "a search
// under this Code" must be given access incl. passwords; this is the section
// the phone question actually turns on), plus the powers that get an officer
// to a lawful search at all: s15 (arrest, how made), s17 (persons present
// where a place is searched under warrant), s23 (arrest WITHOUT warrant —
// sliced 23(1) grounds / 23(2)-(3)), s62 (search of a place without warrant —
// stolen-property only, Inspector+, with the list/declaration/accompany
// conditions officers skip), s116 (investigation search for a document/thing),
// s116A (no-warrant search+seizure — SECURITY OFFENCES / ORGANIZED CRIME only,
// incl. "data"; its scope limit is the citizen's ground). s116C (interception)
// REJECTED: Public-Prosecutor-authorized wiretap, not a stop encounter.
// NOTE — SIBLING FILE: the conditional-rights CPC sections (s19 restraint /
// searching women, s28A rights of persons arrested, s117 remand, s275, s289)
// live in a sibling chunks file authored in parallel. This file keeps ONLY the
// search/arrest/computerized-data cluster — do not add those five here (ID
// collisions). refs into them (e.g. s20 -> s19) are cross-file on purpose.
// AUTHORITY: PDRM. state: ALL — federal. lang: en.
// EN text pdftotext-extracted from the official AGC online version of updated
// text of reprint "As at 1 October 2022" (corpus/raw/act593/en.pdf, latest
// amendment Act A1662 w.e.f. 1 October 2022) → as_at 2022-10-01. Re-derived
// from this reprint after the keeper held the earlier "As at 1 September
// 2017" text stale: every chunked section is word-for-word unchanged between
// the two reprints (A1662 touched none of them) — only as_at moved. The 2022
// extraction is clean of the 2017 -layout artifacts (no stray duplicated
// s23(1) "(f)/(g)/(h)" margin labels; s23(1)(d) "may reasonably be suspected"
// confirmed directly in the text). The chapeau dash in s23(1) is the source's
// U+2015 "―" as printed; em-dashes kept as printed elsewhere.
// KNOWN NEWER LAW: amendment act A1751 (2025) exists beyond this reprint and
// is not yet consolidated by AGC — noted for the corpus-keeper to rule on.
// All chunks verified:false until the corpus-keeper's word-for-word PDF check.
{"id": "CPC-s15-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "15", "kind": "procedure", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "23"}], "heading": "Arrest, how made", "lang": "en", "text": "15. (1) In making an arrest the police officer or other person making the same shall actually touch or confine the body of the person to be arrested unless there is a submission to the custody by word or action.\n(2) If such person forcibly resists the endeavour to arrest him or attempts to evade the arrest such officer or other person may use all means necessary to effect the arrest.\n(3) Nothing in this section gives a right to cause the death of a person who is not accused of an offence punishable with death or with imprisonment for life.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s17-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "17", "kind": "power", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "20A"}], "heading": "Search of persons in place searched under warrant", "lang": "en", "text": "17. Whenever a search for anything is or is about to be lawfully made in any place in respect of any offence all persons found therein may be lawfully detained until the search is completed, and they may, if the thing sought is in its nature capable of being concealed upon the person, be searched for it by or in the presence of a Magistrate or Justice of the Peace or a police officer not below the rank of Inspector.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s20-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "20", "kind": "power", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "20A"}, {"statute": "CPC", "section": "19"}, {"statute": "CPC", "section": "116B"}], "heading": "Search of persons arrested", "lang": "en", "text": "20. Whenever a person is arrested—\n(a) by a police officer under a warrant which does not provide for the taking of bail or under a warrant which provides for the taking of bail but the person arrested cannot furnish bail; or\n(b) without warrant or by a private person under a warrant and the person arrested cannot legally be admitted to bail or is unable to furnish bail,\nthe police officer making the arrest or, when the arrest is made by a private person, the police officer to whom such private person hands over the person arrested may search such person and place in safe custody all articles other than necessary wearing apparel found upon him, and any of those articles which there is reason to believe were the instruments or the fruits or other evidence of the crime may be detained until his discharge or acquittal.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s20A-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "20A", "kind": "procedure", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "20"}], "heading": "Procedure on search of a person", "lang": "en", "text": "20A. (1) Any search of a person shall comply with the procedure on body search as specified in the Fourth Schedule of this Code.\n(2) Notwithstanding any written law, the provisions of the Fourth Schedule shall apply to any search of a person conducted by any officer of any enforcement agency conferred with the power of arrest or search of a person under any law.\n(3) The Minister charged with the responsibility for internal security and public order may amend the Fourth Schedule by order published in the Gazette.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s23-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "23", "subsection": "23(1)", "kind": "power", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "20"}, {"statute": "CPC", "section": "28A"}], "heading": "When police or penghulu may arrest without warrant", "lang": "en", "text": "23. (1) Any police officer or penghulu may without an order from a Magistrate and without a warrant arrest―\n(a) any person who has been concerned in any offence committed anywhere in Malaysia which is a seizable offence under any law in force in that part of Malaysia in which it was committed or against whom a reasonable complaint has been made or credible information has been received or a reasonable suspicion exists of his having been so concerned;\n(b) any person having in his possession without lawful excuse, the burden of proving which excuse shall lie on such person, any implement of housebreaking;\n(c) any person who has been proclaimed under section 44;\n(d) any person in whose possession anything is found which may reasonably be suspected to be stolen or fraudulently obtained property and who may reasonably be suspected of having committed an offence with reference to that thing;\n(e) any person who obstructs a police officer while in the execution of his duty or who has escaped or attempts to escape from lawful custody;\n(f) any person reasonably suspected of being a deserter from the Armed Forces of Malaysia;\n(g) any person found taking precautions to conceal his presence under circumstances which afford reason to believe that he is taking those precautions with a view to committing a seizable offence;\n(h) any person who has no ostensible means of subsistence or who cannot give a satisfactory account of himself;\n(i) any person who is by repute a habitual robber, housebreaker or thief or a habitual receiver of stolen property knowing it to be stolen or who by repute habitually commits extortion or in order to commit extortion habitually puts or attempts to put persons in fear of injury;\n(j) any person in the act of committing in his presence a breach of the peace; or\n(k) any person subject to the supervision of the police who fails to comply with the requirements of section 296.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s23-en-1", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "23", "subsection": "23(2)-(3)", "kind": "power", "heading": "When police or penghulu may arrest without warrant", "lang": "en", "text": "(2) Nothing in this section shall be held to limit or to modify the operation of any other law empowering a police officer or penghulu to arrest without a warrant.\n(3) If any person is arrested without warrant in any component territory of Malaysia (which expression shall in this subsection have the same meaning as in the Warrants and Summonses (Special Provisions) Act 1965 [Act 6 of 1965]) for an offence alleged to have been committed in any other component territory of Malaysia, the provisions of the Warrants and Summonses (Special Provisions) Act 1965, shall, so far as they may be appropriate and with any necessary modifications, apply for the purposes of the custody, transfer, release on bail and appearance before the appropriate Court in the other component territory of Malaysia of that person as if he had been arrested under a warrant issued by a Magistrate in the last mentioned component territory.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s62-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "62", "kind": "power", "heading": "Search without warrant", "lang": "en", "text": "62. (1) If information is given to any police officer, not below the rank of Inspector that there is reasonable cause for suspecting that any stolen property is concealed or lodged in any place and he has good grounds for believing that by reason of the delay in obtaining a search warrant the property is likely to be removed, that officer by virtue of his office may search in the place specified for specific property alleged to have been stolen.\n(2) A list of the property alleged to have been stolen shall be delivered or taken down in writing with a declaration stating that such property has been stolen and that the informant has good grounds for believing that the property is deposited in that place.\n(3) The person from whom the property was stolen or his representative shall accompany the officer in the search.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s116-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "116", "kind": "power", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "116B"}], "heading": "Search by police officer", "lang": "en", "text": "116. (1) Whenever a police officer making a police investigation considers that the production of any document or other thing is necessary to the conduct of an investigation into any offence which he is authorized to investigate and there is reason to believe that the person to whom a summons or order under section 51 has been or might be issued will not or would not produce the document or other thing as directed in the summons or order or when the document or other thing is not known to be in the possession of any person, the officer may search or cause search to be made for the same in any place.\n(2) That officer shall, if practicable, conduct the search in person.\n(3) If he is unable to conduct the search in person and there is no other person competent to make the search present at the time, he may require any officer subordinate to him to make the search, and he shall deliver to the subordinate officer an order in writing specifying the document or other thing for which search is to be made and the place to be searched, and the subordinate officer may then search for the thing in that place.\n(4) The provisions of this Code as to search warrants shall, so far as may be, apply to a search made under this section.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s116A-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "116A", "kind": "power", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "116B"}], "heading": "Search and seizure without warrant", "lang": "en", "text": "116A. (1) Whenever it appears to any police officer not below the rank of Inspector that there is reasonable cause to suspect that there is concealed or deposited in any place any evidence of the commission of a security offence or any offence relating to an organized crime and such police officer has reasonable grounds for believing that, by reason of delay in obtaining a search warrant, the object of the search is likely to be frustrated, he may—\n(a) enter any premises and there search for, seize and take possession of, any book, document, record, account or data, or other article;\n(b) inspect, make copies of, or take extracts from, any book, document, record, account or data;\n(c) search any person who is in or on such premises, and for the purpose of such search detain such person and remove him to such place as may be necessary to facilitate such search, and seize and detain such article, container or receptacle;\n(d) break open, examine, and search any article, container or receptacle; or\n(e) stop, search, and seize any conveyance.\n(2) Whenever it is necessary so to do, a police officer conducting a search under subsection (1) may—\n(a) break open any outer or inner door or window of any premises and enter into, or otherwise forcibly enter the premises and every part thereof;\n(b) remove by force any obstruction to such entry, search, seizure or removal; or\n(c) detain any person found in or on any premises or in any conveyance searched under subsection (1) until such premises or conveyance has been searched.\n(3) No person who is detained under paragraph (2)(c) shall be searched except by a person who is of the same gender as the person to be searched.\n(4) For the purpose of this section, “security offence” means a security offence as specified under the First Schedule to the Security Offences (Special Measures) Act 2012 [Act 747].", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
{"id": "CPC-s116B-en-0", "authority": "PDRM", "statute": "Criminal Procedure Code", "statute_abbr": "CPC", "act_number": "593", "state": "ALL", "section": "116B", "kind": "power", "refs": [{"statute": "CPC", "section": "116"}, {"statute": "CPC", "section": "116A"}, {"statute": "CPC", "section": "20"}], "heading": "Access to computerized data", "lang": "en", "text": "116B. (1) A police officer not below the rank of Inspector conducting a search under this Code shall be given access to computerized data whether stored in a computer or otherwise.\n(2) Any information obtained under subsection (1) shall be admissible in evidence notwithstanding any other provisions in any written law to the contrary.\n(3) For the purpose of this section, “access” includes being provided with the necessary password, encryption code, decryption code, software or hardware and any other means required to enable comprehension of the computerized data.", "source_url": "https://lom.agc.gov.my/act-detail.php?language=BI&act=593", "as_at": "2022-10-01", "verified": true}
